<!DOCTYPE html> <html> <body> <p>For storing media in my application, I decided to go with Amazon's S3 buckets. They are quite popular, feature nice documentation and a big community. Even though S3 is not a standard, its popularity has an impacting influence on other cloud providers that feature compatibility layers with it.</p><p>The bucket used for production is located in London. Below is a screenshot of what it looks like:<br><img src="https://portfolio.drieam.app/api/public/v1/blobs/545ea1b8-b9c6-4fdf-9e1d-cab50ed05fbf/eyJfcmFpbHMiOnsibWVzc2FnZSI6IkJBaHBBM0FlQXc9PSIsImV4cCI6bnVsbCwicHVyIjoiYmxvYl9pZCJ9fQ==--f18627865ca7302b4051b61aa0ebd2da83171b9e/image_2024-03-28_091815808.png" data-key="8ilh25q0sexdzflaca2hqmz3tnsv">The exclamation mark reading Public is due to the bucket being set for public READ only. It features no sensitive content (only photos at this time). Writing is done by a low-privilege account used for production.<br></p><hr><p><br>The bucket is used by the media microservice to upload media and return the links by which it can be accessed. The flow can be visualized by a sequence diagram</p><p><img src="https://portfolio.drieam.app/api/public/v1/blobs/545ea1b8-b9c6-4fdf-9e1d-cab50ed05fbf/eyJfcmFpbHMiOnsibWVzc2FnZSI6IkJBaHBBNHNlQXc9PSIsImV4cCI6bnVsbCwicHVyIjoiYmxvYl9pZCJ9fQ==--809d016d04ac28e0f673586f1846a05fa1f5fb66/image_2024-03-28_093231705.png" data-key="lbqb5vi6p432fjxhtxzs92hv5v1a"><br>This results in an asynchronous media upload which does not block the read/write of listings</p><p></p> </body> </html>